#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:8
#, no-c-format
msgid "&kexec; and &kdump;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: date
#: tuning_kexec.xml:16
#, no-c-format
msgid "2024-03-14"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:23
#, no-c-format
msgid "&kexec; is a tool to boot to another kernel from the currently running one. You can perform faster system reboots without any hardware initialization. You can also prepare the system to boot to another kernel if the system crashes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:30
#, no-c-format
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:32
#, no-c-format
msgid "With &kexec;, you can replace the running kernel with another one without a hard reboot. The tool is useful for several reasons:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:39
#, no-c-format
msgid "Faster system rebooting"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:42
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you need to reboot the system frequently, &kexec; can save you significant time."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:48
#, no-c-format
msgid "Avoiding unreliable firmware and hardware"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:51
#, no-c-format
msgid "Computer hardware is complex and serious problems may occur during the system start-up. You cannot always replace unreliable hardware immediately. &kexec; boots the kernel to a controlled environment with the hardware already initialized. The risk of unsuccessful system start is then minimized."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:60
#, no-c-format
msgid "Saving the dump of a crashed kernel"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:63
#, no-c-format
msgid "&kexec; preserves the contents of the physical memory. After the <emphasis>production</emphasis> kernel fails, the <emphasis>capture</emphasis> kernel (an additional kernel running in a reserved memory range) saves the state of the failed kernel. The saved image can help you with the subsequent analysis."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:72
#, no-c-format
msgid "Booting without &grub; configuration"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:75
#, no-c-format
msgid "When the system boots a kernel with &kexec;, it skips the boot loader stage. The normal booting procedure can fail because of an error in the boot loader configuration. With &kexec;, you do not depend on a working boot loader configuration."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:85
#, no-c-format
msgid "Required packages"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:87
#, no-c-format
msgid "To use &kexec; on &productnamereg; to speed up reboots or avoid potential hardware problems, make sure that the package <systemitem>kexec-tools</systemitem> is installed. It contains a script called <command>kexec-bootloader</command> , which reads the boot loader configuration and runs &kexec; using the same kernel options as the normal boot loader."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:106
#, no-c-format
msgid "To set up an environment that helps you obtain debug information in case of a kernel crash, make sure that the package <systemitem>makedumpfile</systemitem> is installed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:112
#, no-c-format
msgid "The preferred method of using &kdump; in &productname; is through the &yast; &kdump; module. To use the &yast; module, make sure that the package <literal>yast2-kdump</literal> is installed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:119
#, no-c-format
msgid "&kexec; internals"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:125
#, no-c-format
msgid "The most important component of &kexec; is the <filename>/sbin/kexec</filename> command. You can load a kernel with &kexec; in two different ways:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:133
#, no-c-format
msgid "Load the kernel to the address space of a production kernel for a regular reboot:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:137
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;<command>kexec</command> <option>-l</option> <replaceable>KERNEL_IMAGE</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:138
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can later boot to this kernel with <command>kexec</command> <option>-e</option> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:144
#, no-c-format
msgid "Load the kernel to a reserved area of memory:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:147
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;<command>kexec</command> <option>-p</option> <replaceable>KERNEL_IMAGE</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:148
#, no-c-format
msgid "This kernel is booted automatically when the system crashes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:154
#, no-c-format
msgid "To boot another kernel and preserve the data of the production kernel when the system crashes, you need to reserve a dedicated area of the system memory. The production kernel never loads to this area because it must be always available. It is used for the capture kernel so that the memory pages of the production kernel can be preserved."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:162
#, no-c-format
msgid "To reserve the area, append the option <option>crashkernel</option> to the boot command line of the production kernel. To determine the necessary values for <option>crashkernel</option> , follow the instructions in <xref linkend=\"sec-tuning-kexec-crashkernel\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:169
#, no-c-format
msgid "This is not a parameter of the capture kernel. The capture kernel does not use &kexec;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:174
#, no-c-format
msgid "The capture kernel is loaded to the reserved area and waits for the kernel to crash. Then, &kdump; tries to invoke the capture kernel because the production kernel is no longer reliable at this stage. This means that even &kdump; can fail."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:181
#, no-c-format
msgid "To load the capture kernel, you need to include the kernel boot parameters. In most cases, the initial RAM file system is used for booting. You can specify it with <option>--initrd</option> <literal>=</literal> <replaceable>FILENAME</replaceable> . With <option>--append</option> <literal>=</literal> <replaceable>CMDLINE</replaceable> , you append options to the command line of the kernel to boot."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:191
#, no-c-format
msgid "It is required to include the command line of the production kernel. You can simply copy the command line with <option>--append</option> <literal>=</literal> <replaceable>\"$(cat /proc/cmdline)\"</replaceable> or add more options with <option>--append</option> <literal>=</literal> <replaceable>\"$(cat /proc/cmdline) more_options\"</replaceable> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:200
#, no-c-format
msgid "For example, to load the <filename>/boot/vmlinuz-&kernel-version;-default</filename> kernel image with the command line of the currently running production kernel and the <filename>/boot/initrd</filename> file, run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:205
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root; kexec -l /boot/vmlinuz-&kernel-version;-default \\\n"
      " --append=\"$(cat /proc/cmdline)\" --initrd=/boot/initrd"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:208
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can always unload the previously loaded kernel. To unload a kernel that was loaded with the <option>-l</option> option, use the <command>kexec</command> <option>-u</option> command. To unload a crash kernel loaded with the <option>-p</option> option, use <command>kexec</command> <option>-p</option> <option>-u</option> command."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:217
#, no-c-format
msgid "Calculating <option>crashkernel</option> allocation size"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:219
#, no-c-format
msgid "To use &kexec; with a capture kernel and to use &kdump; in any way, RAM needs to be allocated for the capture kernel. The allocation size depends on the expected hardware configuration of the computer, therefore you need to specify it."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:226
#, no-c-format
msgid "The allocation size also depends on the hardware architecture of your computer. Make sure to follow the procedure intended for your system architecture."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:233
#, no-c-format
msgid "Allocation size on &x86-64;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:235
#, no-c-format
msgid "To find out the base value for the computer, run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:238
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;<command>kdumptool</command> calibrate\n"
      "Total: 49074\n"
      "Low: 72\n"
      "High: 180\n"
      "MinLow: 72\n"
      "MaxLow: 3085\n"
      "MinHigh: 0\n"
      "MaxHigh: 45824 "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:246
#, no-c-format
msgid "All values are given in megabytes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:251
#, no-c-format
msgid "Take note of the values of <literal>Low</literal> and <literal>High</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:256
#, no-c-format
msgid "Significance of <literal>Low</literal> and <literal>High</literal> values"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:257
#, no-c-format
msgid "On &x86-64; computers, the <literal>High</literal> value stands for the memory reservation for all available memory. The <literal>Low</literal> value stands for the memory reservation in the DMA32 zone, that is, all the memory up to the 4 GB mark. <remark> Petr Tesarik says in bsc#948565 that High means \"all memory\". This is not true in SLE 12 SP1 RC1, but fixed for SLE 12 SP1 RC2. - sknorr, 2015-10-05 </remark>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:268
#, no-c-format
msgid "<remark>The following is confusing, but probably true ( https://bugzilla.suse.com/show_bug.cgi?id=948565#c6 ). - sknorr, 2015-10-05 </remark> SIZE_LOW is the amount of memory required by 32-bit-only devices. The kernel allocates 64M for DMA32 bounce buffers. If your server does not have any 32-bit-only devices, everything should work with the default allocation of 72M for <literal>SIZE_LOW</literal> . A possible exception to this is on NUMA machines, which may make it appear that more <literal>Low</literal> memory is needed. The &kdump; kernel may be booted with <literal>numa=off</literal> to make sure normal kernel allocations do not use <literal>Low</literal> memory."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:285
#, no-c-format
msgid "Adapt the <literal>High</literal> value from the previous step for the number of LUN kernel paths (paths to storage devices) attached to the computer. A sensible value in megabytes can be calculated using this formula:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:291
#, no-c-format
msgid "SIZE_HIGH = <replaceable>RECOMMENDATION</replaceable> + (<replaceable>LUNs</replaceable> / 2)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:298
#, no-c-format
msgid "SIZE_HIGH"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:299
#, no-c-format
msgid "The resulting value for <literal>High</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:307
#, no-c-format
msgid "The value recommended by <command>kdumptool calibrate</command> for <literal>High</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:316
#, no-c-format
msgid "The maximum number of LUN kernel paths that you expect to ever create on the computer. Exclude multipath devices from this number, as these are ignored. To get the <emphasis>current</emphasis> number of LUNs available on your system, run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:323
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.user; cat /proc/scsi/scsi | grep Lun | wc -l"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:328
#, no-c-format
msgid "If the drivers for your device make many reservations in the DMA32 zone, the <literal>Low</literal> value also needs to be adjusted. However, there is no simple formula to calculate these. Finding the right size can therefore be a process of trial and error."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:334
#, no-c-format
msgid "For the beginning, use the <literal>Low</literal> value recommended by <command>kdumptool calibrate</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_kexec.xml:345
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you are changing the kernel command line directly"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:350
#, no-c-format
msgid "crashkernel=<replaceable>SIZE_HIGH</replaceable>,high crashkernel=<replaceable>SIZE_LOW</replaceable>,low"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:351
#, no-c-format
msgid "Replace the placeholders <replaceable>SIZE_HIGH</replaceable> and <replaceable>SIZE_LOW</replaceable> with the appropriate value from the previous steps and append the letter <literal>M</literal> (for megabytes)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:360
#, no-c-format
msgid "crashkernel=<replaceable>36M</replaceable>,high crashkernel=<replaceable>72M</replaceable>,low"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_kexec.xml:364
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you are using the &yast; GUI:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:366
#, no-c-format
msgid "Set <guimenu>Kdump Low Memory</guimenu> to the determined <literal>Low</literal> value."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:370
#, no-c-format
msgid "Set <guimenu>Kdump High Memory</guimenu> to the determined <literal>High</literal> value."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_kexec.xml:377
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you are using the &yast; command line interface:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:379
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:382
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;yast kdump startup enable alloc_mem=<replaceable>LOW</replaceable>,<replaceable>HIGH</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:383
#, no-c-format
msgid "Replace <replaceable>LOW</replaceable> with the determined <literal>Low</literal> value. Replace <replaceable>HIGH</replaceable> with the determined <literal>HIGH</literal> value."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:395
#, no-c-format
msgid "Allocation size on &power; and &zseries;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:397
#, no-c-format
msgid "To find out the basis value for the computer, run the following in a terminal:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:401
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;<command>kdumptool</command> calibrate"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:402
#, no-c-format
msgid "This command returns a list of values. All values are given in megabytes."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:407
#, no-c-format
msgid "Write down the value of <literal>Low</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:412
#, no-c-format
msgid "Adapt the <literal>Low</literal> value from the previous step for the number of LUN kernel paths (paths to storage devices) attached to the computer. A sensible value in megabytes can be calculated using this formula:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:418
#, no-c-format
msgid "SIZE_LOW = <replaceable>RECOMMENDATION</replaceable> + (<replaceable>LUNs</replaceable> / 2)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:419
#, no-c-format
msgid "The following parameters are used in this formula:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:425
#, no-c-format
msgid "SIZE_LOW"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:426
#, no-c-format
msgid "The resulting value for <literal>Low</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:433
#, no-c-format
msgid "RECOMMENDATION"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:434
#, no-c-format
msgid "The value recommended by <command>kdumptool calibrate</command> for <literal>Low</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:442
#, no-c-format
msgid "LUNs"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:443
#, no-c-format
msgid "The maximum number of LUN kernel paths that you expect to ever create on the computer. Exclude multipath devices from this number, as these are ignored."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:453
#, no-c-format
msgid "The values now need to be set in the correct location."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_kexec.xml:458
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you are working on the command line"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:460
#, no-c-format
msgid "Append the following kernel option to your boot loader configuration:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:463
#, no-c-format
msgid "crashkernel=<replaceable>SIZE_LOW</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:464
#, no-c-format
msgid "Replace the placeholder <replaceable>SIZE_LOW</replaceable> with the appropriate value from the previous step and append the letter <literal>M</literal> (for megabytes)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:469
#, no-c-format
msgid "As an example, the following is valid:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:472
#, no-c-format
msgid "crashkernel=<replaceable>108M</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: tuning_kexec.xml:476
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you are working in &yast;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:478
#, no-c-format
msgid "Set <guimenu>Kdump Memory</guimenu> to the determined <literal>Low</literal> value."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:489
#, no-c-format
msgid "Excluding unused and inactive CCW devices on &zseries;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:490
#, no-c-format
msgid "Depending on the number of available devices the calculated amount of memory specified by the <option>crashkernel</option> kernel parameter may not be sufficient. Instead of increasing the value, you may alternatively limit the amount of devices visible to the kernel. This lowers the required amount of memory for the <emphasis>crashkernel</emphasis> setting."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:499
#, no-c-format
msgid "To ignore devices you can run the <command>cio_ignore</command> tool to generate an appropriate stanza to ignore all devices, except the ones currently active or in use."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:504
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;cio_ignore -u -k\n"
      "cio_ignore=all,!da5d,!f500-f502"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:506
#, no-c-format
msgid "When you run <command>cio_ignore -u -k</command> , the blocklist becomes active and replaces any existing blocklist immediately. Unused devices are not being purged, so they still appear in the channel subsystem. But adding new channel devices (via CP ATTACH under z/VM or dynamic I/O configuration change in LPAR) treats them as blocked. To prevent this, preserve the original setting by running <command>sudo cio_ignore -l</command> first and reverting to that state after running <command>cio_ignore -u -k</command> . As an alternative, add the generated stanza to the regular kernel boot parameters."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:518
#, no-c-format
msgid "Now add the <option>cio_ignore</option> kernel parameter with the stanza from above to <envar>KDUMP_CMDLINE_APPEND</envar> in <filename>/etc/sysconfig/kdump</filename> , for example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:523
#, no-c-format
msgid "KDUMP_COMMANDLINE_APPEND=\"cio_ignore=all,!da5d,!f500-f502\""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:526
#, no-c-format
msgid "Activate the setting by restarting <systemitem class=\"service\">kdump</systemitem> :"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:530
#, no-c-format
msgid "systemctl restart kdump.service"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:536
#, no-c-format
msgid "Basic &kexec; usage"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:538
#, no-c-format
msgid "To use &kexec;, ensure the respective service is enabled and running:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:544
#, no-c-format
msgid "Make sure the &kexec; service is loaded at system start:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:547
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;systemctl enable kexec-load.service"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:550
#, no-c-format
msgid "Make sure the &kexec; service is running:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:553
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;systemctl start kexec-load.service"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:557
#, no-c-format
msgid "To verify if your &kexec; environment works properly, try rebooting into a new Kernel with &kexec;. Make sure no users are currently logged in and no important services are running on the system. Then run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:564
#, no-c-format
msgid "systemctl kexec"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:566
#, no-c-format
msgid "The new kernel previously loaded to the address space of the older kernel rewrites it and takes control immediately. It displays the usual start-up messages. When the new kernel boots, it skips all hardware and firmware checks. Make sure no warning messages appear."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:574
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using &kexec; with the reboot command"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:575
#, no-c-format
msgid "To make <command>reboot</command> use &kexec; rather than performing a regular reboot, run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: tuning_kexec.xml:579
#, no-c-format
msgid "ln -s /usr/lib/systemd/system/kexec.target /etc/systemd/system/reboot.target"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:580
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can revert this at any time by deleting <filename>etc/systemd/system/reboot.target</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:587
#, no-c-format
msgid "How to configure &kexec; for routine reboots"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:589
#, no-c-format
msgid "&kexec; is often used for frequent reboots. For example, if it takes a long time to run through the hardware detection routines or if the start-up is not reliable."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:595
#, no-c-format
msgid "The firmware and the boot loader are not used when the system reboots with &kexec;. Any changes you make to the boot loader configuration are ignored until the computer performs a hard reboot."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:601
#, no-c-format
msgid "Basic &kdump; configuration"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:603
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can use &kdump; to save kernel dumps. If the kernel crashes, it is useful to copy the memory image of the crashed environment to the file system. You can then debug the dump file to find the cause of the kernel crash. This is called <quote>core dump</quote> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:610
#, no-c-format
msgid "&kdump; works similarly to &kexec; (see <xref linkend=\"cha-tuning-kexec\"/> ). The capture kernel is executed after the running production kernel crashes. The difference is that &kexec; replaces the production kernel with the capture kernel. With &kdump;, you still have access to the memory space of the crashed production kernel. You can save the memory snapshot of the crashed kernel in the environment of the &kdump; kernel."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:620
#, no-c-format
msgid "Dumps over network"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: tuning_kexec.xml:621
#, no-c-format
msgid "In environments with limited local storage, you need to set up kernel dumps over the network. &kdump; supports configuring the specified network interface and bringing it up via <systemitem>initrd</systemitem> . Both LAN and VLAN interfaces are supported. Specify the network interface and the mode (DHCP or static) either with &yast;, or using the <option>KDUMP_NETCONFIG</option> option in the <filename>/etc/sysconfig/kdump</filename> file."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: tuning_kexec.xml:633
#, no-c-format
msgid "Target file system for &kdump; must be mounted during configuration"
